      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was triggered by a synchronous systems collapse of the palace redistributive economies due to a common vulnerability: over-specialized, brittle administrative structures that failed when a prolonged drought caused simultaneous harvest failures across the region.\", \"mechanism\": \"Palatial centers in Mycenaean Greece, Hittite Anatolia, and the Levant (e.g., Ugarit) shared a deep structural dependence on surplus extraction and redistribution of grain, oil, and wine to support specialized labor (scribes, soldiers, artisans). A multi-year drought, evidenced by paleoclimate proxies, caused cascading crop failures. The administrative systems, optimized for stability, lacked the flexibility to adapt quickly. Famine eroded the legitimacy of the ruling elites, leading to internal revolts and the rapid abandonment of the economic centers. The physical destruction layers are explained by internal factional violence, not just external invasion.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean palace centers (Pylos, Mycenae)\", \"Hittite capital Hattusa\", \"Ugarit\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\", \"Cyprus (initially)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Archaeological evidence shows a significant increase in grain storage capacity and diversification of food sources in the decades immediately preceding the destruction of Pylos and Hattusa.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The destruction layers at all major sites are consistently and solely attributable to a single, massive earthquake storm with no evidence of prior social stress or burning.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This account explains the simultaneity and the specific collapse of complex, centralized states while allowing for Egypt's survival due to the Nile's more reliable, drought-resistant floodplain agriculture, which buffered its redistributive economy. It reframes the 'Sea Peoples' as a symptom of the collapse (displaced populations) rather than the primary cause.\"}",
