      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was a consequence of a pandemic introduced via the newly intensified trade networks, which selectively devastated the densely populated palatial centers and their administrative classes, leaving a power vacuum that was filled by secondary migrations.\", \"mechanism\": \"The palace civilizations were connected by a high-volume, long-distance trade network in goods and people (diplomats, merchants, slaves). This network acted as an ideal vector for a highly virulent pathogen to which these interconnected urban populations had no immunity. The disease, perhaps a hemorrhagic fever or early smallpox, swept through the administrative and craft-specialist quarters of the palaces, killing the very people who maintained the economic and political system. The subsequent 'invasions' and burnings were opportunistic, carried out by surviving rural or peripheral populations moving into the suddenly undefended and depopulated urban centers.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Levantine city-states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Bioarchaeological analysis of human remains from the destruction layers shows no evidence of a novel pathogen; all pathologies are consistent with endemic diseases and trauma.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The destruction layers universally show evidence of prolonged, organized siege warfare and street-by-street fighting, not a rapid, opportunistic occupation of an already-dead city.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This explains the suddenness and the specific targeting of elite centers. Egypt's survival is attributed to its more dispersed rural population along the Nile and its natural quarantine barriers (deserts), which slowed the pathogen's spread enough for the state to mount a response. The 'Sea Peoples' are a secondary effect: displaced survivors fleeing the plague-ravaged north.\"}",
